<App layout="vertical">
  <AppHeader>
    <Text fontWeight="bold">Bram</Text>
    <Theme paddingHorizontal-Button-sm="$space-1">
      <HStack gap="$space-0_5">
        <Button
          label="A−"
          variant="ghost"
          tooltip="Decrease app font size"
          onClick="window.setAppFontSize(window.getAppFontSize() - 1)" />
        <Button
          label="A+"
          variant="ghost"
          tooltip="Increase app font size"
          onClick="window.setAppFontSize(window.getAppFontSize() + 1)" />
      </HStack>
    </Theme>
  </AppHeader>

  <VStack padding="$space-6" gap="$space-4" maxWidth="640px">
    <Markdown content="# Welcome

This is the Bram project. Unless you are developing this
project, you probably want to launch `bram` in a directory
that contains your own app, which might be an XMLUI app or any web
app. Then use the top-toolbar `agent tools` button to open the
drawer with seven views:

- **Transcript** — the current agent session's transcript
  (user/assistant turns plus tool activity), shown as a reader rather
  than a live control surface.
- **Worklist** — pending items the agent has proposed
  (`resources/worklist.json`); approve or drop with one click.
- **Commits** — recent commits with one-click push.
- **Issues** — open / closed GitHub issues for the current repo (via
  the local `gh` CLI), with one-click to file a new one.
- **Sessions** — read/search past Claude and Codex transcripts.
- **Context** — the active provider's durable local context sources:
  Claude shows `CLAUDE.md`, imports, memory, hooks, and settings;
  Codex shows repo-local `AGENTS.md` plus local Codex config,
  memories, and rules.
- **README** — this project's README for quick reference." />
  </VStack>
</App>
